+## 📌 CVE-2000-0548 – Buffer Overflow in Kerberos 4 Error Message Handling
+
+- **Component:** Kerberos 4 Key Distribution Center (KDC)
+- **Issue:** Buffer overflow in `kerb_err_reply` when handling long error messages (`e_msg`)
+- **Impact:** Remote attackers could exploit this to execute arbitrary code or crash the service
+- **Upstream Status:** ❗ Affects **only Kerberos 4**, deprecated and removed from MIT Kerberos by 2005  
+  → [MIT Kerberos](https://web.mit.edu/kerberos/)  
+  → [Alpine Security Tracker – No Entry Found](https://security.alpinelinux.org)
+
+### Vulnerable Versions (Alpine)
+| Release   | Package      | Status       |
+|-----------|--------------|--------------|
+| 3.18      | krb5-libs    | Not Affected |
+
+### Why You Can't Fix This
+
+- ✅ **Alpine never included Kerberos 4** in its repositories; it was deprecated before Alpine gained popularity
+- ✅ Alpine only ships **MIT Kerberos 5**, which does not contain the affected `kerb_err_reply` code
+- ✅ Alpine uses **musl libc**, which is incompatible with many legacy codebases like Kerberos 4
+- ✅ The **Alpine CVE tracker has no record** of CVE-2000-0548 ever affecting any package
+- ✅ Alpine's modern krb5-libs is built from patched upstream MIT sources and never exposed the vulnerable code path
+
+**✅ Recommendation:**  
+Treat this CVE as a **scanner false positive** for Alpine containers. There is no vulnerable code in the krb5-libs package, and no remediation is necessary or applicable.
+
+---
+
+## Summary
+
+- CVE-2000-0548 affects Kerberos 4, not Kerberos 5
+- Alpine Linux only includes modern, patched versions of Kerberos 5
+- There is no vulnerable code in Alpine's krb5-libs package
+- Alpine’s ecosystem and tooling (musl libc, modern packages) prevent legacy code from being used
+
+**📌 Best Practice:**  
+Document this CVE as a **non-issue** for Alpine-based workloads and exclude it from actionable vulnerability reports.
+
