+## Why You Cannot Fix `krb5-libs` Vulnerabilities via Code Patching in Containers
+
+## Overview: What Is `krb5-libs`?
+
+`krb5-libs` provides the core libraries for MIT Kerberos, a widely used authentication protocol designed to provide secure user identity verification. Alpine Linux includes only the modern MIT Kerberos 5 libraries, not the obsolete Kerberos 4 implementation.
+
+---
+
+## Why Vulnerabilities in `krb5-libs` Are Often Not Fixable in Containers
+
+Security scanners (Trivy, Grype, etc.) often generate false positives due to:
+
+- Historical CVEs linked to obsolete components no longer present in modern distributions  
+- Superficial version or package name matching without examining actual source code  
+- Incomplete awareness of how Alpine packages are built (e.g., use of musl libc)  
+
+Manual intervention to "fix" krb5 CVEs in Alpine containers can:
+
+- Lead to unnecessary image bloat or instability  
+- Mismatch expectations from upstream secure-by-default design  
+- Introduce confusion in audits and patch management  
+
+---
+
+# ⚠️ CVE Breakdown
+
+Below are details of a CVE frequently flagged but not applicable to Alpine-based containers:
+
+---
+
+## 📌 CVE-2000-0546 – Buffer Overflow in Kerberos 4 `set_tgtkey` Function
+
+- **Component:** Kerberos 4 Key Distribution Center (KDC)  
+- **Issue:** Buffer overflow in the `set_tgtkey()` function due to unsafe handling of the `lastrealm` variable  
+- **Impact:** Remote attackers could trigger a denial-of-service or potentially execute arbitrary code  
+- **Upstream Status:** ❗ Affects **only Kerberos 4**, which was deprecated and removed from MIT Kerberos by the mid-2000s  
+  - [MIT Kerberos](https://web.mit.edu/kerberos/)  
+  - [Alpine Security Tracker – No Entry Found](https://security.alpinelinux.org)
+
+### Vulnerable Versions (Alpine)
+
+| Release | Package     | Status        |
+|---------|-------------|----------------|
+| 3.18    | krb5-libs   | Not Affected   |
+
+### Why You Can't Fix This
+
+- ✅ **Alpine never included Kerberos 4** in its repositories; it was deprecated before Alpine gained popularity  
+- ✅ Alpine only ships **MIT Kerberos 5**, which does not contain the affected `set_tgtkey` function  
+- ✅ Alpine uses **musl libc**, which is incompatible with legacy Kerberos 4 code  
+- ✅ The **Alpine CVE tracker has no record** of CVE-2000-0546 ever affecting any package  
+- ✅ The `krb5-libs` package in Alpine is built from patched upstream MIT Kerberos 5 sources, with no exposure to vulnerable code  
+
+**✅ Recommendation:**  
+Treat this CVE as a **scanner false positive** for Alpine containers. There is no vulnerable code in the krb5-libs package, and no remediation is necessary or applicable.
+
+---
+
+## Summary
+
+- CVE-2000-0546 affects Kerberos 4, not Kerberos 5  
+- Alpine Linux only includes modern, patched versions of Kerberos 5  
+- There is no vulnerable code in Alpine's krb5-libs package  
+- Alpine’s ecosystem and tooling (musl libc, modern packages) prevent legacy code from being used  
+
+**📌 Best Practice:**  
+Document this CVE as a **non-issue** for Alpine-based workloads and exclude it from actionable vulnerability reports.
+
+---
+
